–Male":"1339–Deceased","1277–Male":"1277–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1306":"about 1306","about 1339":"about 1339","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","1306":"1306","Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Newcombe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Newcomb  .","Possibly an Americanized form of German <b>Neukamm</b> (see   Newcomb   2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Newcomb","meanings":["English: nickname for a new arrival in a place, from Middle English <i>newe-comen</i>, <i>newe-come</i> ‘newly arrived, recently come’ (Old English <i>nīwe</i> + <i>cumen</i>, <i>cuma</i>). The intrusive <i>-b-</i> is the result of the influence of placenames ending in Old English <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’ (see   Coombe  ). No such placename as <i>Newcombe</i> is actually on record in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Neukamm</b>, possibly arising from a misinterpretation of its etymology as <i>neu</i> ‘new’ + <i>Kamm</i> ‘comb’ (see   Neukam  ).","History: According to family tradition, Capt. Andrew Newcomb was born in England in 1618 and died in Boston, MA, in 1686, leaving family who settled both in MA and in Kittery, ME. Among his descendants was the internationally renowned astronomer Simon Newcomb (1835–1909)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":9,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":22,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":31,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":76,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert le Newcombe was born about 1306, in Lincolnshire, England, his father, Walter Newcom, was 31 and his mother, Alice Lakesby, was 43. He had at least 1 son with Alice Sumercotts. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1306–":"umbes 1306–Surnud","1306–Male":"1306–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1306":"umbes 1306","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","1306":"1306","Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1306–":"noin 1306–Kuollut","1306–Male":"1306–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","1277–Male":"1277–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1306":"noin 1306","about 1339":"noin 1339","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1265":"1265","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","1306":"1306","Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleetby Saint Clement, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1306–":"environ 1306–Décédé","1306–Male":"1306–Décédé","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","1339–Male":"1339–Décédé","1277–Male":"1277–Décédé","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","about 1306":"